entry.title: Always send mouse up event to main frame during autoscroll selection
entry.content:
We usually route mouse event to the renderer frame that painted the

part of screen that the mouse cursor is currently over. However, there

is cases where mouse down started in main frame and user drag over to

the OOP child frame. The mouse up event was routed to the child frame.

However, the main frame still has autoscroll selection started and is

waiting for next mouse event. Since the mouse event was delivered to

the child frame, this makes the main frame stuck in the autoscroll

state.



Fix is to send a message from main render frame to the browser process

input routing code when there is ongoing autoscroll selection. We will

dispatch mouse up events to both the OOP child frame and main frame

when the state is active.

entry.content:
To support more flexible grouping of tests when specifying tests in

starlark, declarations of the tests that know what type they are will be

used. This will allow declaring a bundle that mixes compile targets and

tests of different types rather than only being able to compose tests of

the same types into a suite.

declaring GPU telemetry tests, gtest tests, isolated script tests, junit

tests and script tests. The existing functions for declaring targets

have been renamed so that they are accessed via the isolates struct to

provide a more clear separation of the concepts. There are two

exceptions to this: the compile_target function is kept as-is since it

doesn't produce an isolate entry that can be referenced for running a

test and the junit_test function is replaced by the one on the tests

struct since it will now define a test that can be referenced by suites.

entry.title: [omnibox][ml] Refactor debouncing
entry.content:
go/autocomplete-controller-refactor has some details on the refactor

plan.



This is part 4 of the refactor.



Autocomplete controller debounces notifying observers when new results

are ready. This CL makes 2 changes:



1) Replaces `AutocompleteProviderDebouncer::ResetTimeLastRun()` with

`FlushRequest()`. The latter is simpler to understand, it just

flushes any pending requests. They serve the same purpose: to support

running some notifications immediately instead of debounced.



2) Instead of `AutocompleteController::DelayedNotifyChanged()` deciding

whether to debounce or not based on the controller's internal state,

its callsites will determine whether to debounce or not and pass an

`immediate` param to `DelayedNotifyChanged()`. This is 1 step towards

making the controller's methods rely on params instead of params &

internal state, which makes it hard to keep track of which code paths

do what.

entry.title: Don't configure ALPS protocols that aren't also configured in ALPN
entry.content:
SSLClientSocketImpl currently configures all application_settings values

in BoringSSL, however BoringSSL's API docs say not to do this:

https://commondatastorage.googleapis.com/chromium-boringssl-docs/ssl.h.html#SSL_add_application_settings



We probably should make BoringSSL not only catch this case but also

normalize the order to match the ALPN list. In the meantime, fix the

Chromium call site to be correct. There were a few places where we'd

send "h2" in ALPS but not ALPN:



- In response to HTTP_1_1_REQUIRED from HTTP/2

- WebSockets connections



Fix this by iterating over the ALPN list and only paying attention to

map keys that appear in there. It does mean the callers in the other

cases are passing down values that are ignored, but that's not a huge

deal in the grand scheme of things.



See also discussion here:

https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/5064051/comment/cfc4cb1b_cda4ca01/

entry.content:
The existing logic of laser pointer assumes that the device scale factor

or display rotation will not change during a laser gesture. However, it

using laser pointer in tablet mode). This can result in the existing

laser segment being drawn in the wrong position (either translated or

scaled incorrectly).



This CL destroys the LaserPointerView if the root window bounds change

in order to reset the existing assumptions.

entry.title: GIF Decoder Resilient Error Handling by Skipping Faulty Frames.
entry.content:
Modify the logic of GIF decoding in order to skip the current

erroneous frame and continue decoding the next frame when encountering

decoding errors, rather than terminating the entire GIF decoding

process.



SetFailedFrameIndex records the index of the failed frame during

decoding. If all frames fail to decode, call SetFailed to release

the current decoder.



IsFailedFrameIndex checks if the current frame has failed decoding.

If it has failed, it terminates the decoding process for the current

frame.

entry.title: [OOPIF PDF] Fix saving full-page edited PDFs by saving by PDF plugin
entry.content:
Add plumbing for the browser to request the PDF plugin to save. The PDF

plugin needs to save if the PDF has any edits. A save event will be

dispatched to the PDF extension and forward to the PDF plugin if the PDF

Viewer should handle the save. The PDF Viewer already knows how to

receive save events and save PDFs.



Create save event chrome.pdfViewerPrivate.onSave, similar to

chrome.mimeHandlerPrivate.onSave, for the PDF extension to listen to

save events and forward it to the PDF plugin.



Create pdf_extension_util::MaybeDispatchSaveEvent(), which dispatches

the save event to a specific PDF Viewer if the PDF plugin needs to

handle the save.



Add plugin_can_save_ to PdfViewerStreamManager::StreamInfo and the API

to set and get it, so the browser can know when the PDF plugin should

handle save events.



For the SavePage() browser command, allow the PDF viewer a chance to

handle the save instead, otherwise let the browser handle the save.



See https://crrev.com/633448 for more context.



Low-Coverage-Reason: TESTS_IN_SEPARATE_CL Tests for browser command PDF

saving will be added in the future. https://crbug.com/1511110. Tests for

ChromePdfDocumentHelperClient are currently disabled for OOPIF PDF and

will be enabled in the future.

entry.title: [PM] Initially set a process node to high priority
entry.content:
Upon adding a process node to the graph, the ProcessPriorityPolicy

dispatch a call to set the OS priority of the process to the

initially low priority of the process node.



This is wrong because a process node is always added to the graph

empty, but a high priority frame could be in the process of being

added which would immediately cause the process' priority to change

to high. This happens when starting Chrome.



With this change, ProcessPriorityAggregator now knows that a new

process node temporarily has a high priority, until the first

execution context added to the process determines its initial

priority.



This will avoid having the initial renderer of the initial navigation

being backgrounded for a split second.

entry.title: Initialize FeatureList even if Chrome will early-exit
entry.content:
In the browse, base::FeatureList initialization normally happens at the

//chrome layer and needs to come after various other systems are started

up. However, in some cases, Chrome can early-exit before the FeatureList

is fully initialized. But in at least one of these cases (the

--pack-extension commandline switch, which packs an extension and

immediately exits) requires the FeatureList to be initialized, since

we parse the extension as part of the packing process and extension

parsing requires checking th state of base::Features.



Modify the browser startup behavior to allow the //content layer to

create the base::FeatureList if the browser will exit before the

base::FeatureList would otherwise be created. This ensures there's

a valid value for the FeatureList (and it's okay if the initialized

values of the features wouldn't match those in a running version of

Chrome).



After this, we can do a partial revert of crrev.com/ea7ee982c6b804ed.

entry.title: Multiplanar: Always fallback from R16F to L16F and add early return
entry.content:
Always fallback from GL_R16F to GL_LUMINANCE16F formats. This is needed

as with GLCommonBacking, GLTextureHolders are created per plane which

always have SinglePlaneFormat::LUMINANCE16F as there is no equivalent

R16F for 16f bit format and thus use GL_LUMINANCE16F. But with

multiplanar, we can have 16f channel format which does correspond to

LUMINANCE16F as well but we might end up with GL_R16F storage format

when texture_rg extension is supported. This adjusts so that we always

fallback to GL_LUMINANCE16F for 16f channel formats.



Also, FakeSkiaOutputSurface currently does not implement support for

MakePromiseSkImageFromYUV. This also updates MakePromiseSkImage to

return early for multiplanar formats which can be taken as we create

TextureDrawQuads instead of YUVVideoDrawQuads
